00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:21.940 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, I'm Taru Spiegel
from the Library's European Division

00:00:21.940 --> 00:00:26.330
and welcome to this program about
Jean Sibelius and Fritz Kreisler.

00:00:26.330 --> 00:00:29.400
And many thanks to the Embassy
of Finland, Keijo Karjalainen

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.940
and the Library's Music
Division, Anne McClain,

00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:34.480
David Plylar [phonetic]
and Jen Loritson [phonetic]

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:36.500
for making the event possible.

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:38.070
Also the great technical staff

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:41.530
who makes us look professional,
thank goodness.

00:00:41.530 --> 00:00:43.530
We're happy to have Jani Lehtonen

00:00:43.530 --> 00:00:46.980
and Jani Aarrevaara
as our speakers today.

00:00:46.980 --> 00:00:50.200
And, let me tell you, it was
very, very hard to get 2 speakers

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:53.360
with the same first name
[laughter], but we managed.

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:57.080
And we also get extra points
because the names Jani and Jean,

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:59.710
as in Jean Sibelius are related.

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:03.200
As you know, this year marks the
150th anniversary of the birth

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.220
of Jean Sibelius, whose
actual birthday was yesterday.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:10.370
And we're glad to remember this
great Finnish composer and also

00:01:10.370 --> 00:01:13.550
to highlight one of the Library's
treasures, the original manuscript

00:01:13.550 --> 00:01:16.220
of the Fritz Kreisler
piano arrangement

00:01:16.220 --> 00:01:20.890
of Sibelius's lovely violin
concerto "Opus 47 D Minor".

00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:25.250
And the treasure is right
there, being guarded by David.

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:28.320
And why and when this Kreisler
reduction was made is a mystery

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:31.040
that today's speakers
will look into.

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:34.800
Sibelius was born in
Finland in 1865 and Kreisler

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.270
in Austria, 10 years later.

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:39.360
Both were extremely
famous in their lifetime

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:42.550
and are still well loved
by audiences worldwide.

00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:45.180
Today's talk will focus on
a lesser known conjunction

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:47.350
of these superstars.

00:01:47.350 --> 00:01:49.980
I would like to mention that the
Library's holdings include more

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.980
than an thousand titles
relating to Sibelius.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:55.700
Also, unique here, is the
Fritz Kreisler collection

00:01:55.700 --> 00:02:00.310
which includes manuscripts,
personal papers and correspondence.

00:02:00.310 --> 00:02:05.420
The music division serves
materials for your music inquiries

00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:07.590
and the European Division
would be the place to go

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:11.040
to for various European
language materials including

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:14.170
Finnish material.

