piano on the faculty

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:00.810
of the Tampere Music Conservatory.

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:03.230
He graduated from [inaudible]
Music Academy

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:05.460
and received his concert diplome

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:07.920
under the direction of
Erik Apel [phonetic].

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:09.750
He has taught piano
at various Finnish

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.390
and German music institutions.

00:03:12.390 --> 00:03:14.680
One of Aarrevaara's awards
led to a concert tour

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:18.070
that included Carnegie Hall--
a Carnegie Hall performance

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:21.700
and his repertoire consists
of chamber music and lead.

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:26.050 position:56%
And together the Janis published a
Kreisler CD in 2012, they're working

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:29.590
on another one that's
looking for a publisher

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:33.310
that features this
Kreisler reduction.

00:03:33.310 --> 00:03:37.480
And they've done a lot of
research on this material.

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:40.190
We hope to see it published
maybe one day.

00:03:40.190 --> 00:03:41.610
Finally, for the fun bit,

00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:43.810
please note that the
event is being videotaped

00:03:43.810 --> 00:03:46.610
and please turn your
cell phones off.

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:53.100
So, I'll have a little talk
here with Jani Lehtonen.

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:58.150
So, Janie, what led you here to
talk about Kreisler and Sibelius?

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:03.480
&gt;&gt; When Jani Aarrevaara and I
made our first joint recording

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:07.050
of Fritz Kreisler's work
for violin and piano,

00:04:07.050 --> 00:04:10.970
I learned a lot about
Kreisler's life.

00:04:10.970 --> 00:04:16.170
Our CD published in 2012 contains
a number of known, and less known,

00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:19.810
compositions created by
this master violinist

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:24.010
and composer during
his remarkable career.

00:04:24.010 --> 00:04:28.410
When writing the booklet for the
CD, [inaudible] excellent biography

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:35.190
of Fritz Kreisler, "Love's Joy,
Love's Sorrow" was a great help.

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:41.850
It is possibly the most
comprehensive work in this area.

00:04:41.850 --> 00:04:44.220
Biancolli's book ends
with a complete listing

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:48.570
of Kreisler's work made
during his lifetime.

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:52.290
Looking at this, my
interest was sparked

00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:58.650
by the Sibelius violin concerto
Opus 47 D Minor arrangement

00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:00.440
for piano and violin.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.330
&gt;&gt; So you had mentioned that
this was a big surprise,

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:05.540
this information about manuscript?

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:10.120
&gt;&gt; Yes. The information about
the Sibelius arrangement was

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:13.360
so interesting for a Finnish
violinist that I began

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:17.190
to investigate where I could
find the music material.

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:20.590
The Biancolli's list
of works stated only

00:05:20.590 --> 00:05:24.190
that this was an unpublished
work held here

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:26.480
at the U.S. Library of Congress.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:31.750
I spoke about the matter with some
well-informed people in Finland,

00:05:31.750 --> 00:05:37.400
and it turned out that the Finnish
National Radio Library had a copy

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.310
of the Library of Congress
manuscript

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:43.780
which is over there on the table.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:47.520
I received a top duplicate copy

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.690
from them [inaudible]
library [inaudible].

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:55.640
At this stage, I still
didn't know what to expect

00:05:55.640 --> 00:06:00.130
because Kreisler had made a number
of published and, thus well-known,

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:04.740
arrangement of violin concertos
by different composers as well

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:12.020
as other works whose structure
he had completely changed.

00:06:12.020 --> 00:06:14.190
One can therefore rather
speak about these

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:18.630
as new compositions using
someone else's technique.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:22.710
This, however, was not the
case regarding the Sibelius

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:24.380
violin concerto.

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:28.890
Kreisler had kept the solo violin
part unchanged, in other words,

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:32.310
just as Sibelius had composed it,

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:37.100
except for some very
minor violinist details

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:40.710
which may be considered
editorial suggestions rather

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:43.270
than actual changes.

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:48.990
&gt;&gt; So when you found the manuscript
copy, what was your next step?

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:51.930
What did you decide to do?

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:58.550
&gt;&gt; We decided to actually
record the whole thing.

00:06:58.550 --> 00:07:06.440 position:56%
It was so good that it would be nice

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:11.100
for other people really
hear that music.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:21.680
And, actually, the background music
when you came in this hall was

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:29.110
from the CD made by us last year.

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:35.220
And we are now waiting for
a publisher for this CD.

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:44.310
&gt;&gt; So you did a considerable
amount of research

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:47.380
on the Kreisler reduction.

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:51.350
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Despite our
efforts, we have been unable

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:54.940
to find any written references
about the Kreisler piano reduction

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:58.770
of the Sibelius violin
concert, so all the conclusions

00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:01.570
about this version are our own.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:04.910
Why Fritz Kreisler made
his own piano reduction

00:08:04.910 --> 00:08:08.980
of the Sibelius concerto
remains a great mystery so far,

00:08:08.980 --> 00:08:12.520
especially since Sibelius
also made his own reduction

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:16.020
of the piece in 1905.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:21.180
Also the date of the
Kreisler reduction is unknown.

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:27.180 position:56%
Future research may clarify if Jean
Sibelius had time to work the violin

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:31.360
and orchestra concerto into
his 1905 arrangement for piano

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:34.660
and violin before Kreisler
made his own version.

00:08:34.660 --> 00:08:39.090
Did Fritz Kreisler and
Jean Sibelius ever meet?

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:42.320
Both are historic superstars
in their day

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:45.540 position:56%
and were only 10 years apart in age.

00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:51.600
As far as we know, Kreisler
visited Finland twice and, thus,

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:54.380
a meeting would have been possible.

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:57.360
Did Sibelius know about
Kreisler's piano reduction

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:00.190
and did Kreisler have the
composer's permission?

00:09:00.190 --> 00:09:02.030
We don't know.

00:09:02.030 --> 00:09:06.040
From the point of view of research
into the recent history of music,

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:10.900
it would be most enlightening to
find answers to these questions.

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:12.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Okay, I have just a little aside.

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:16.490
I was reading a little bit about
Kreisler and I'm not sure if he got

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:20.780
to Finland this time, but
he was playing in Russia

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:24.480
and met a Finnish girl and wanted
to leave everything behind.

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:27.600
This was when he was
young and foolish, right?

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:28.900
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:30.700
&gt;&gt; But he was persuaded
to go back [laughter].

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:33.750
So, anyway, what do you
think was the reason

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:35.820
for the Kreisler reduction?

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:42.410 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Generally speaking, the events
that revolutionized musical culture,

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:47.810
radio and records, also radically
changed music consumption habits.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:52.440
Before this breakthrough, it was
only possible to enjoy live music.

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.720
This meant that mostly only
the upper classes were able

00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:58.890
to pursue music at the high level.

00:09:58.890 --> 00:10:03.980
It has also largely affected
how music was published.

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:09.530
For instance, Felix Mendelssohn
Bartholdy secured a contract

00:10:09.530 --> 00:10:13.980
from his publisher for the famous
E Minor Concerto for Violin

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:17.030
and Orchestra only on condition

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.110
that he also prepare a
piano reduction based

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:24.530
on the orchestration
as soon as possible.

00:10:24.530 --> 00:10:28.090
In other words, classical
music in its own time was first

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:30.950
and foremost consumer music.

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:36.890
It was performed not just at actual
concerts, but at home in silence

00:10:36.890 --> 00:10:42.430 position:56%
and for festive occasions often with
a reduced configuration not least

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:46.540
because of the various
more number of orchestras.

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:47.960
&gt;&gt; So about a hundred years ago,

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:52.940
you and Jani Aarrevaara would have
been playing this piece at home

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:56.590
for your friends and family
or at some local event?

00:10:56.590 --> 00:10:57.890
&gt;&gt; Correct.

00:10:57.890 --> 00:10:59.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah?

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:03.220
&gt;&gt; In times past, recital concerts
were far more common than today.

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:09.140 position:56%
The artist would either play or sing
most often to piano accompaniment.

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:12.940
This seems strange to us
today because we are used

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:15.700
to hearing live performances
for solo instruments

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:20.140
or orchestras only as
a part of a concert.

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:24.540
Even until the Second World War,
it was usual for violin recitals

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:29.010
to feature a violin concerto with
piano accompaniment in addition

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:32.860
to music similarly
configured for the program.

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:38.000
During Fritz Kreisler's career,
this was not at all uncommon.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.680 position:56%
The fact that he created a reduction

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:45.070
for the Sibelius violin
concerto definitively indicates

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:49.770
that the work made a
significant impression on him

00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:53.880
because a reduction requires
a lot of work and time.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:12:01.400
And I can show you, it is
really a huge amount of work.

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:04.570
These are our copies of
the original manuscript

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:09.950
which you can look at on the table.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:16.250
It's 39 pages handwrited music.

00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:27.290
It's really great job he has
done so I would say it takes

00:12:27.290 --> 00:12:34.180
at least weeks just to
write this whole thing.

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:45.230
But he also made this great work of
arranging the whole concerto again

00:12:45.230 --> 00:12:50.950
from the big orchestral
score for piano score.

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:55.210
&gt;&gt; So was the Sibelius
concerto well-known

00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:59.430
when Sibelius composed
it in 1904, right?

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:02.430
&gt;&gt; Yeah. I would say yes and no

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:09.240
because the first time it
was performed in Helsinki,

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:16.410
the first version, it wasn't
very successful thing.

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:24.210 position:56%
And, afterwards, Sibelius made huge
corrections for his violin concerto.

00:13:24.210 --> 00:13:29.820
And this is a revised
version we nowadays know

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:32.570
and hear soloists playing.

00:13:32.570 --> 00:13:35.640
And this Kreisler's
work is also based

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:39.070
on this revised Sibelius
violin concerto.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:48.090
And but it wasn't very famous
before Jascha Heifetz recorded it.

00:13:48.090 --> 00:13:54.490
But, afterwards, it has been maybe
the most successful violin concerto

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:56.070
ever composed.

00:13:56.070 --> 00:14:03.450
And nowadays, the amount of
recordings is over 60 recordings

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:07.880
of Sibelius violin
concerto so it means

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:12.590
that it is most recorded
violin concerto ever composed

00:14:12.590 --> 00:14:15.240
on 20th century.

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:19.490
&gt;&gt; So, Jascha Heifetz made
this known in the '30s, right?

00:14:19.490 --> 00:14:20.790
&gt;&gt; Yes, I think so.

00:14:20.790 --> 00:14:22.090
It was in the '30s.

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:23.560
&gt;&gt; So, it wasn't really
such a super, super,

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:27.030
super hit when Kreisler
did the reduction, so.

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:28.900
&gt;&gt; No, no, that's right.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:33.010
&gt;&gt; So, any conclusions about
the Kreisler reduction?

00:14:37.950 --> 00:14:44.650
&gt;&gt; I would say that,
like I said before,

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:52.570
he was a really great
affected about Sibelius music.

00:14:52.570 --> 00:15:02.630
And we have to remember that
he was extremely gifted person

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:06.890
as a violinist, but
also as a composer.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:14.080
When he got the place from Vienna
Conservatory at 7 years old,

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:19.840
his first teacher was
Anton Bruckner really.

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:25.370
And composing was also
main part on his studies.

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:33.850
And he was remarkably talented
to produce music by heart

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:38.100
and also arrange other
composers' works

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:40.700
for his own instrument especially.

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:43.820 position:56%
But he was also really good pianist.

00:15:43.820 --> 00:15:47.240
So that's why this reduction

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:52.960
for Sibelius concerto
is really interesting.

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:59.920
And I would say it's a real
treasure for violinists, pianists

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:04.460
and also music lovers
all over the world.

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:06.960
&gt;&gt; So the quality is good,
you said, yeah, yeah.

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:09.240
&gt;&gt; Yes, it's, it's brilliant.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:10.540
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:14.400 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So, as was mentioned before,
Sibelius also created an arrangement

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:19.270
of this concerto so what
are the differences?

00:16:19.270 --> 00:16:24.330
&gt;&gt; I think we could ask
this from other Jani now,

00:16:24.330 --> 00:16:27.600
he has some kind of show so.

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:28.960
&gt;&gt; Should I start with the show?

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:30.260
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:32.560
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:46.270
&gt;&gt; So, hello.

00:16:46.270 --> 00:16:53.100
Yes, in the following, I
will present some notes

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:57.040
on Kreisler's reduction
in comparison

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:01.570
with Sibelius's own reduction.

00:17:01.570 --> 00:17:09.940
I will also play some samples
from our CD and some samples

00:17:09.940 --> 00:17:18.030
with the orchestra,
a couple of samples.

00:17:18.030 --> 00:17:24.880
Apparently, there are at least 3
reductions of Sibelius's concerto,

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:30.410
Sibelius's own reduction
from 1905 like we just heard

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:37.060
from the same time when he finished
his second version, last version,

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:43.650
of the concerto, a reduction
by Alexandre Gretchaninoff,

00:17:43.650 --> 00:17:51.130
a Russian composer from 1942 which,
according to Sibelius's secretary,

00:17:51.130 --> 00:17:56.930
Santeri Levas, was
